text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to their own comment on this

Day 2 of building the most UNFUNDABLE startup in the world.


From my last post, it's clear that people are tired of the noise.

Tired of following people they've never talked to.
Tired of group chats being flooded with reels.
Tired of drifting from friends, even though we're as online as ever.

But just because we feel this way doesn't mean we're always on the lookout for a solution.

The reason is simple: FOMO.
We'll never get off Instagram or TikTok because that feels like we're cutting ties with the rest of the world.

So what's the strategy?
Positioning.

Instagram and Tiktok are no longer social platforms.
They're a short-form entertainment system, much like youtube.

What we position Dayli as is a REAL social platform. 
Not for mutuals three connections apart.
But for your friends who you want to be in contact with FOR LIFE.

Here's the question for today:
Is there anyone who drifted from your life that you wish you could've stayed in touch with?

text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Alex Lambs comment on this

Im not cracked. 

Nor do I actually want to be. 


The truth is, Im here by complete accident. 

Six months ago, I started to go down a rabbit hole.

I was curious why the music industry wasnt paying attention to the education space in music tech. 

I wanted change after so many friends were frustrated scavenging for resources to learn music production. 

I knew we could change that. 

I had no idea how. 

The past six months, I doubled down on obsessions: music tech, startups, and learning how people learn. 

I chatted with producers, re-analyzed my workflows in Ableton, and finally learned what PMF stood for. 

Every obsession became Virtuoso, and that made me more addicted to this whole process.

Still, Im not trying to build the next unicorn, get into a prestigious accelerator, or even want to be a Linkedin top voice. 

Im here because of a problem 3 million producers face that an industry stays silent on, and I know were the only ones that can solve it. 

Im not here to be cracked. 

Im here for the love of the game.

text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Hunter Earls comment on this

If you dont have a stache, youre ngmi. 



While everyone is chasing consistency, theres a group of people that are chasing something completely different. 

I call these people mustaches.

Like growing a mustache, they're dedicated to the details. Every hair matters. They're building part-to-whole, chasing purpose.

Because in order to be chasing purpose, you have to be grounded in something deeper: dedication.

Dedication is different from consistency.

You can show up everyday, but youll be chasing virality. 

Virality without purpose leads to nothing. 

But if youre dedicated, devoted to chasing your purpose, youll find that consistency doesnt become something you chase. 

It becomes a byproduct of your mission. 

So how do we become more dedicated?

Simple. Its all in the DETAILS.

Understanding that whatever youre building is built part-to-whole. 

If youre dedicated to bringing every little thing to its best version, youre going to have something truly valuable.

That takes time. A lot of time.

But I guarantee you whatever you build will be something extraordinary.

Driven by dedication, fueled by purpose. 

HUGE thank you to Aadi V. for being the inspiration for this post.

I SLEPT WITH A BILLIONAIRE



Spent the day (and night) with another billionaire and honestly the biggest thing that stuck with me wasnt money or flexes, it was how intentional everything felt. The way they think is truly, just different. One thing they kept repeating was always keep yourself first, invest in yourself before anything else, your skills, your mind, your environment. Everything else comes after.

They also broke down their rule with money and honestly its stupid simple. Spend 10 percent of what you earn, THATS IT. The other 90 percent gets saved, invested, or put back into things that compound. No lifestyle flex, no trying to look rich, just letting time do the heavy lifting and sitting back. 

Another billionaire officially added to The Eighth Day Club  and this is exactly why were building it the way we are. Real conversations, real operators, real lessons you dont get just scrolling online.

If you want to be part of what were building, DM me. Were putting together what I genuinely believe will be the greatest society of entrepreneurs in the world.

REMEMBER, Move slow, think long, dont blow it all too fast 😉

If you're an artist or work within a record label, you'd want to see this.

Clipy is expanding into music.

Specifically: TikTok / Instagram for artists and record labels.

Heres the reality:
Most songs dont fail because of quality.
They fail because distribution doesnt scale and attention is expensive.
Just post more isnt a strategy.

Weve already proven this model.

We bootstrapped Clipy to 7 figures in under 5 months.
 - Generated 2B+ views across our network.
 - All performance-based. No paid ads dependency.

Now were applying the same infrastructure to music.
What this means:
 - Performance-based TikTok promotion
 - Thousands of posts under your audio
 - Content that keeps moving after spend stops

If youre a record label or an artist looking for real distribution, DM me music. We'll discuss from there.

text.text: Rayyan Aquino replied to Aaryan Khannas comment on this

Cincinnati is not the next SF 


Its different, and the core reason lies in its DNA. 

San Francisco is the gold rush city. You have to be constantly innovating to survive. 

High risk, high reward.

Cincinnati is all about first principles, home to giants like Procter & Gamble and GE. 

Its grounded in the grind.

Now youd think that bringing startup culture to the Queen City would end up failing miserably. 

But theres little pockets of startups EVERYWHERE. 

From StartupCincy to Cintrifuse Capital to the 1819 Innovation Hub, there are communities, VCs, and accelerators thriving in every neighborhood. 

And as a high school founder, I had no idea. 

The thing is, Cincinnati is missing something that first principles wont tell you: the best ideas are where you least expect them to be. 

Im a believer in that as a music tech founder. Virtuoso isnt anything that people expect. 

But the Mason Venture Studio confirmed that belief for me.

7 startups, all high school students, all following the Queen City approach: ground yourself in first principles, then ship fast. 

You wouldnt expect that. 

No one would. 

As a city, we need to understand our foundations, but not let them define us. 

We need to expect the unexpected, ground ourselves in what makes us unique, and build in public. 

One community. One city. Strength in Unity. 

Thats how we build.

If youre a founder or investor in Cincinnati, lets connect. Theres so much to come in 2026.

text.text: Rayyan Aquino commented on this

hey linkedin, meet my girlfriend


she exists somewhere between exam schedules, late nights, and too many open tabs.

Tasrae is my first serious startup.

id built things before, but this was the first time i committed to something even when life was already full. i started her almost two years ago right as exams were kicking off. which explains why my chatgpt wrapped decided to call me out for it.

the idea came from frustration. finance tools either dumb things down or bury you in complexity. nothing really helped you understand what uncertainty looks like, especially if you werent already fluent in the math.

so i started building.

tasrae combines complex mathematics. monte carlo simulations, bayesian reasoning, risk modeling, with ai that compute AND teaches. its an edtech-first platform designed to do the heavy lifting and explain whats happening in quantitative financial modeling as you go, so users learn while they model.

some days tasrae broke. some days she worked better than expected. all of it taught me more about discipline, focus, and tradeoffs than any class ever could.

i joke and call her my girlfriend, but anyone whos built their first serious thing knows the feeling. nights of dispair, love, happiness, grief. when youre learning and building at the same time, it stops being just a project.

so hey linkedin, this is my girlfriend.
she showed up during exams, made my life harder,
and ended up teaching me the most.

i almost didnt go.



ive really only got two real shots at submitting papers before college apps. the labs barely open. every minute is supposed to be productive.

then i remembered...
that's the mindset that gets you clowned in the bay.

Sidharth Swaminathan, Omkar Anand, and Akhil Manikandan. the most cracked dudes at the institute. somehow a Granger and Lowes run turned into the best night ive had all week.

surprise In-N-Out orders.
drives though the city blasting drake.    (guess who?)
ended at Sierra Open Space Preserve, looking over all of San Jose. the airport. our lab. my parents store in downtown.

im not saying fun beats productivity. it doesnt.
but youll never find the right people locked in your room pretending thats discipline.

the convos went from where do you see yourself in ten years to how do you actually train your anterior mid-cingulate cortex. 5am runs. eating clean. building things that matter.

if youre optimizing every minute and still feel stuck, youre not broken. youre just missing the room.

comment ROOM or DM me if you're also building circles just like this.
~ what are you building.
